'''Conor Classon''' is an Irish sportsperson from Rosbeg, [[County Donegal]]. He plays [[Gaelic football]] with his local club [[C.L.G. Ard an Rátha|Ardara]], representing them at all levels, and has been a member of the [[Donegal GAA|Donegal]] senior inter-county team.

==Playing career==
Classon did not play at minor level but his rookie year came in 2010.<ref name=rookie_hard_work>{{cite news|url=http://www.donegaldemocrat.ie/sport/rookie-classon-not-afraid-of-hard-work-1-2003995|title=Rookie Classon not afraid of hard work|work=Donegal Democrat|date=26 April 2010|accessdate=26 April 2010|archive-url=https://archive.is/20140502193654/http://www.donegaldemocrat.ie/sport/rookie-classon-not-afraid-of-hard-work-1-2003995|archive-date=2 May 2014|dead-url=yes}}</ref>

Along with club teammates [[Paddy McGrath]] and [[Peter McNelis]],<ref>{{cite news|first=Frank|last=Craig|url=http://www.ardara.ie/Article_Details.aspx?article_id=599&tscategory_id=82|title=Cadbury's Ulster Under-21 Football final|work=Ardara.ie|quote=Ardara trio Conor Classon, Paddy McGrath and Peter McNelis all played their part in helping Jim McGuinness' men secure a famous win over the Breffni blues. Both Classon and McGrath were again two of the side's most influential operators - with McNelis entering the fray late in the second half.|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130217165643/http://www.ardara.ie/Article_Details.aspx?article_id=599&tscategory_id=82|archivedate=2013-02-17|df=}}</ref> he was part of the Donegal U21 squad which qualified for the All-Ireland U21 Final.<ref name=Gavin_vs_McGuinness>{{cite news|first=Fintan|last=O'Toole|url=https://www.the42.ie/donegal-michael-murphy-859156-Apr2013/|title=Remember the last time that Jim Gavin managed against Jim McGuinness?: The opposing managers in tomorrow's Division 1 league tie in Ballybofey have come face to face before|work=[[The42.ie]]|date=6 April 2013|accessdate=6 April 2013}}</ref> He had earlier played for Donegal in the final of the [[Ulster Under-21 Football Championship]] in 2010.<ref name=Ulster_U21FC_08042010>{{cite news|url=http://www.hoganstand.com/article/index/126826|title=Ulster U21FC: Murphy leads Donegal to title|work=[[Hogan Stand]]|date=8 April 2010|accessdate=8 April 2010}}</ref>

Classon made a substitute appearance in the [[2014 National Football League (Ireland)|2014 National Football League]] Division 2 Final against [[Monaghan GAA|Monaghan]] at [[Croke Park]], replacing [[Odhrán Mac Niallais]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thescore.ie/donegal-monaghan-live-2-1435104-Apr2014/|title=LIVE: Donegal v Monaghan, Division 2 football league final|work=The Score|date=27 April 2014|accessdate=27 April 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140427221937/http://www.thescore.ie/donegal-monaghan-live-2-1435104-Apr2014/|archive-date=27 April 2014|dead-url=yes}}</ref>
Known for his Scandinavian physique, he is valued for his strength, pace and his good hands.<ref name=rookie_hard_work/>

==Honours==
* [[All-Ireland Under-21 Football Championship]] runner-up: 2010<ref name=Gavin_vs_McGuinness/>
* [[Ulster Under-21 Football Championship]]: 2010<ref name=Ulster_U21FC_08042010/>

